#!/usr/bin/env python3
r"""
RL_backtester.py  --  Bandit Q-learning backtester: learn Q(s,a) for 3 actions
(NO_TRADE, BUY_YES, BUY_NO) using ALL requested DB columns as FEATURES and run a
sequential simulator.

NEW CHANGE (your request):
- If the agent chooses BUY_YES or BUY_NO at time t:
    1) Buy that side immediately at current ASK (leg 1).
    2) After `--hedge-delay-ms` (default 3000ms), buy the OPPOSITE token in
       EQUAL CONTRACT QTY at the ASK available at/after that time (leg 2).
- Reward target for RL is based on whether the *pair cost* after the hedge buy
  is <= `--pair-cost-threshold` (default 0.99).
  Pair cost = ask_leg1 + ask_leg2  (both are token prices in [0,1] dollars).
- Backtest models the same thing:
    - It schedules the hedge leg and executes it at the first row >= due time.
    - When the hedge leg executes, it books a "locked profit" (no settlement delay):
        locked_profit_usd = (1.0 - pair_cost) * qty
      (This is the economic arbitrage profit if you truly hold both sides to settlement,
       ignoring fees/slippage. You can still add per-trade penalties / half-spread costs.)
    - It also reports the success rate: pair_cost <= threshold.

NOTES / ASSUMPTIONS:
- Token prices are in *dollars* (e.g., 0.52 = 52 cents). So "0.99 cents" is treated
  as $0.99 (99 cents). Use --pair-cost-threshold to change.
- If the needed future ask is unavailable within the same slug, that action's target is 0
  (NO_TRADE) for training; and in backtest the pending hedge will be dropped at slug boundary.

Run (PowerShell):
  cd "C:\Users\antho\OneDrive\Desktop\5minute";
  $env:KMP_DUPLICATE_LIB_OK="TRUE";
  python btc_latency\RL_backtester.py `
    --db "C:\Users\antho\OneDrive\Desktop\5minute\btc_latency\rl_live_trades_march_first.db" `
    --extra-train-db "C:\Users\antho\OneDrive\Desktop\5minute\btc_latency\trader_log.snapshot.db" `
    --train-slugs 0-8 --test-slugs 9-11 --epochs 10 --device cpu `
